I started my QA journey during my internship, where I performed manual testing on various cryptocurrency wallets such as MetaMask, Coinbase, and Binance. 
This was my first hands-on experience in testing, where I worked on both testnet and mainnet environments to understand real-world application behavior.
After that, in my second company, I worked on Shopify-based websites and web applications. 
One of the major projects I contributed to was an Ice Hockey Soccer Board system, where I tested 12 different user roles along with its mobile application. 
My responsibilities included performing smoke, sanity, and regression testing to ensure system stability across different user flows.
I also worked on a Business Intelligence (BI) tool named Prism, which included 12–15 data preparation tools. 
These tools allowed users to modify, transform, and retrieve data in multiple ways. 
Additionally, I tested data visualization features, including graphs inspired by Power BI, ensuring accuracy and usability.
Currently, I am working on WordPress-based websites along with an LMS (Learning Management System) platform designed for kids. 
This system consists of two parts: a website and a platform. 
Users purchase courses or digital books through the website and, after payment, are redirected to the platform where they can access their content. 
For additional purchases, users are redirected back to the website.
My testing workflow involves analyzing requirements and understanding product features, creating detailed test plans (including user stories and acceptance criteria), and designing structured test cases based on those requirements. 
These test cases are then shared with the development team to align implementation. 
Once the feature is developed, I verify it against the test cases and report any issues by logging bugs or creating new tickets. 
I always test from a user’s perspective rather than just a tester’s perspective to ensure better product quality.
